;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 6: Feel — Deadzones and Ease

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      6
  :title               "Feel: Deadzones and Ease"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"You have a game. Physics is honest, collisions register, the ship
thrusts, the paddle catches. The kid plays it for five minutes and puts
it down. Your friend's game — same shape, same code density — plays for
an hour. What is the difference?

FEEL. The thousand tiny corrections between raw physics and something a
human enjoys. Camera lag so the ship doesn't jitter. Ease curves so
rotation doesn't snap. Screen-shake sized to impact velocity. Coyote
time so the jump is generous. Input buffers so the fire is responsive.
Sound cued a half-frame before the visual so the ear leads the eye.

This chapter is 90% code that will look almost identical to earlier
chapters — you'll see the ship-with-thrust from chapter 3 twice, side
by side, before and after tuning. The lesson is that FEEL is code. It
is not vibes. It is `tick/ease`, `motion/with-feel`, `world/camera-shake!`
tuned to the right coefficients. Every microsecond has a shape.

We do a before-and-after study on one game so the kid can SEE the
difference. Then we build a knob-tuning workbench that lets you
adjust ten parameters live and feel the change.

---

## 6.1 Before — the raw game

Chapter 3's ship, unpolished.

```scheme
;; Ship + thrust, no polish. Play for 30 seconds. Note how it FEELS.
(define ship-angle 0)
(define (raw-ship)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/drag! ship 0.01)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (set! ship-angle (- ship-angle 0.10)))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle 0.10)))
       (when (input/down? 'a)
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
               (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship))))
           (entity/set-vel! ship
                            (+ vx (* 0.20 (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                            (+ vy (* 0.20 (geom/sin ship-angle))))))
       (world/step)
       (world/camera-follow! ship 1 0 0)   ;; instant follow — 1.0 factor
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)))))

(big-bang raw-ship)
```

Play this. Rotate the ship — it feels snappy but slightly wrong.
Thrust — the camera glued to the ship makes the WORLD look like it
moves, not the ship. Fine for a static shooter; nauseating in a space
game where the ship is the thing.

The rotation is instant. The thrust is instant. The camera is instant.
Everything is instant. That is what earlier chapters teach for
clarity. But instant is not what the human hand wants.

---

## 6.2 After — the polished game

Same game, tuned.

```scheme
;; Same ship, with camera lag, rotation ease, thrust ease, screen shake.
(define ship-angle 0)
(define rot-vel 0)      ;; rotation velocity — accumulates over frames
(define thrust-charge 0) ;; how long 'a' has been held

(define (polished-ship)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/drag! ship 0.01)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       ;; Rotation with ease — velocity ramps up over 8 frames.
       (cond
         ((input/down? 'left)
          (set! rot-vel (max -0.08 (- rot-vel 0.01))))
         ((input/down? 'right)
          (set! rot-vel (min  0.08 (+ rot-vel 0.01))))
         (else
          ;; No input — decay rotation velocity.
          (set! rot-vel (* rot-vel 0.85))))
       (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle rot-vel))
       ;; Thrust with charge — hold 'a' longer for more thrust.
       (if (input/down? 'a)
           (set! thrust-charge (min 1.0 (+ thrust-charge 0.08)))
           (set! thrust-charge (* thrust-charge 0.90)))
       (when (> thrust-charge 0.02)
         (let ((vx (car (entity/vel ship)))
               (vy (cadr (entity/vel ship)))
               (thrust (* 0.20 (tick/ease thrust-charge))))
           (entity/set-vel! ship
                            (+ vx (* thrust (geom/cos ship-angle)))
                            (+ vy (* thrust (geom/sin ship-angle))))))
       (world/step)
       ;; Camera with lag — factor 0.08 = smooth follow, deadzone 40x30.
       (world/camera-follow! ship 0.08 40 30)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)))))

(big-bang polished-ship)
```

Play THIS one. Rotate — the ship eases into rotation, holds a
constant spin while held, coasts to a stop when released. Thrust — the
first tap gives a small nudge; hold gives a full push. Camera — the
ship can wander within a 40×30 rect at screen center before the camera
begins to move; then the camera catches up smoothly.

Same physics. Same verbs. Different coefficients. Radically different
feel.

`tick/ease x` is a smoothstep — takes a linear 0-to-1 and returns an
S-curve 0-to-1 that starts slow, accelerates through the middle, eases
into 1. It is the single most-used feel primitive in games. Whenever
you have 'a parameter changes over time and abrupt looks bad,' wrap it
in `tick/ease`.

---

## 6.3 The eight knobs

Appendix H tabulates. Here is the shortlist every arcade game tunes.

**1. Acceleration.** How fast do you reach max speed from a standstill?
Small = deliberate; large = twitchy. Fighter jets: large. Trucks:
small.

**2. Deceleration.** How fast do you stop when input releases?
Independent of acceleration! Fast decel = precise. Slow decel = drifty.
Space games tune decel low.

**3. Apex hang.** For jumping games: how long does the player spend
at the top of the arc? `entity/gravity-scale! player 0.7` while
`vy < 0.5` for a hangtime effect. See chapter 7.

**4. Coyote time.** After walking off a ledge, how many frames can the
player still jump? Typically 4-8 frames. See chapter 7 and Appendix F.

**5. Jump buffer.** If the player presses jump N frames BEFORE landing,
buffer the press so it fires on landing. Typically 6-10 frame buffer.

**6. Screen shake.** How much does the screen shake on impact? Scale
with impact velocity. `(world/camera-shake! (* impact-vel 0.3) 0.85)`.
Decay factor 0.85 = 3-4 frame shake; 0.98 = 10+ frames.

**7. Sound pitch.** On impact, `(audio/play 'hit)` at pitch scaled by
impact velocity gives a satisfying variety. Even without pitch control,
alternating between two sounds ('hit1', 'hit2') on successive impacts
reduces monotony.

**8. Sound volume.** Softer sounds for background events, louder for
critical. Use `audio/master-volume` to duck all audio during dialogue.

---

## 6.4 A knob-tuning workbench

Wire the knobs to buttons so you can tune live.

```scheme
;; A ship you can retune while it flies.
;; 'a' fire; up/down adjust selected knob; left/right change knob.
(define ship-angle 0)
(define rot-vel 0)
(define knob-index 0)
(define knobs (vector 0.01   ; 0: rot-accel
                      0.08   ; 1: rot-max
                      0.85   ; 2: rot-decay
                      0.20   ; 3: thrust-per-frame
                      0.90   ; 4: thrust-decay
                      0.08   ; 5: camera-lag
                      40     ; 6: camera-dead-x
                      30))   ; 7: camera-dead-y
(define knob-names '#(\"rot-acc\" \"rot-max\" \"rot-dec\"
                     \"thr\" \"thr-dec\"
                     \"cam-lag\" \"dead-x\" \"dead-y\"))
(define thrust-charge 0)

(define (tuning-bench)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/drag! ship 0.01)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       ;; Knob switching.
       (when (input/pressed? 'left)
         (set! knob-index (max 0 (- knob-index 1))))
       (when (input/pressed? 'right)
         (set! knob-index (min 7 (+ knob-index 1))))
       ;; Knob adjustment.
       (when (input/down? 'up)
         (vector-set! knobs knob-index
                      (+ (vector-ref knobs knob-index)
                         (if (< knob-index 5) 0.001 0.5))))
       (when (input/down? 'down)
         (vector-set! knobs knob-index
                      (- (vector-ref knobs knob-index)
                         (if (< knob-index 5) 0.001 0.5))))
       ;; Rotation using knobs.
       (let ((rot-acc (vector-ref knobs 0))
             (rot-max (vector-ref knobs 1))
             (rot-dec (vector-ref knobs 2))
             (thr     (vector-ref knobs 3))
             (thr-dec (vector-ref knobs 4))
             (cam-lag (vector-ref knobs 5))
             (dead-x  (vector-ref knobs 6))
             (dead-y  (vector-ref knobs 7)))
         ;; Rotation.
         (cond
           ((input/down? 'a) (set! rot-vel (min rot-max (+ rot-vel rot-acc))))
           ((input/down? 'b) (set! rot-vel (max (- rot-max) (- rot-vel rot-acc))))
           (else (set! rot-vel (* rot-vel rot-dec))))
         (set! ship-angle (+ ship-angle rot-vel))
         ;; Thrust.
         (set! thrust-charge (* thrust-charge thr-dec))
         ;; (no explicit thrust button in this bench — you're tuning rot)
         (world/step)
         (world/camera-follow! ship cam-lag dead-x dead-y)
         (paint-clear)
         (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)
         (paint-text (string-append (vector-ref knob-names knob-index)
                                    \": \"
                                    (number->string (vector-ref knobs knob-index)))
                     10 220))))))

(big-bang tuning-bench)
```

The kid selects a knob with left/right, adjusts with up/down, and
watches the ship's behavior change in real time. Turning `rot-acc`
from 0.001 to 0.05 goes from stately to instant. Turning `rot-dec`
from 0.85 to 0.99 makes the ship spin down slowly after release. The
knob values that FEEL right are the ones the kid keeps.

This is how real game designers tune. Get the game running end-to-end,
then spend a week on knobs.

---

## 6.5 motion/with-feel and motion/with-pace

The runtime exposes two feel-shaping primitives worth knowing.

`motion/with-feel target amount` adds micro-jitter to a motion so it
feels alive instead of robotic. Applied to a character's sprite: a
tiny wobble on step, breath-cycle-scale variation.

`motion/with-pace target curve` reshapes the timing of a motion
without changing endpoints. A ball can travel from A to B in the same
duration but with an ease-in, ease-out, or linear pace.

```scheme
;; A ship whose sprite wobbles subtly during coast.
(define (feel-wobble)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((ship (world/spawn 'ship 160 120)))
    (entity/shape! ship 'triangle 12)
    (entity/set-vel! ship 1 0)
    (motion/with-feel ship 0.5)   ;; 0.5-unit wobble
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'ship (entity/x ship) (entity/y ship) 12 12)))))
```

Subtle. The kid may not consciously see it. But turn it off and the
motion feels sterile. That is the wobble's whole job.

---

## 6.6 Impact-scaled shake

Not all impacts deserve the same shake. A tap-collision should not
rattle the screen; a boss-hit should. Scale shake by impact velocity.

```scheme
;; On any collision, shake proportional to impact speed.
(define (impact-scaled-shake)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (world/floor! 240)
  (let ((ball (world/spawn 'ball 160 20)))
    (entity/bounce! ball 0.85)
    (entity/shape! ball 'circle 6))
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (world/step)
     ;; Check ball's downward velocity when it touches the floor.
     (world/each 'ball
                 (lambda (b)
                   (when (and (>= (entity/y b) 234)
                              (> (cadr (entity/vel b)) 1.0))
                     (world/camera-shake! (* (cadr (entity/vel b)) 0.5)
                                          0.85))))
     (paint-clear)
     (world/each 'ball
                 (lambda (b) (paint-cell 'ball (entity/x b) (entity/y b) 6 6))))))

(big-bang impact-scaled-shake)
```

The first bounce shakes hard. Subsequent bounces shake less because
velocity has decayed. The screen tells the kid, without words, that
the ball is losing energy.

---

## 6.7 The four patterns for feel

**Composition.** Feel is composed. A polished ship = raw ship +
rotation-ease + thrust-ease + camera-lag + shake. Each layer costs a
few lines. Together they transform the play experience. Composition of
feel-layers is how a game gets great.

**Orchestration.** Order-of-application matters. Poll BEFORE update.
Update BEFORE draw. Apply screen shake to camera AFTER the shot's
impact registers. If you shake before the collision this frame, you
show yesterday's shake for today's hit — subtly wrong.

**In-routing.** Feel affects the in-routing itself. An 8-frame input
buffer changes how buttons ROUTE — a fire pressed 6 frames before
landing still routes to fire, arriving on the landing frame. That
delay is invisible to the player and invaluable to the feel.

**Routing.** Feel routes back out to display (camera shake), audio
(pitch/volume), and sometimes back to input (rumble via haptic
routing). Feel is the OUTBOUND polish on every action.

---

## 6.8 Common desktop tasks

**Shop-cursor deadzone.** In a shop's browsing UI, cursor movement can
be given a small deadzone (0.5 mm equivalent) before scrolling begins.
Kids scrolling on a shaky bus don't accidentally scroll past their
target. Same math as camera deadzone.

**Purchase-confirmation ease.** After 'buy', the button smoothly eases
into a checkmark shape over 12 frames rather than instantly swapping.
The tick/ease call is the same one your ship uses. Physics of UI
transitions is UI FEEL.

---

## 6.9 Pitfalls

**Everything too smooth.** Over-easing makes controls feel sluggish
and unresponsive. There is a bar — too twitchy is uncomfortable, too
smooth is uncomfortable, and the sweet spot is narrow. Playtest.

**Camera shake nauseating.** Shake magnitude scales linearly but
perception is exponential. Cap total shake at 20 pixels. Decay fast.

**Deadzone hides bugs.** A deadzone that suppresses tiny input can
also suppress input from a broken joystick you should be reporting.
Log raw input in dev mode.

**Buffered input replays after death.** If the player dies with 'a'
still in the input buffer, don't fire on respawn. Clear the buffer.

**Feel-tuning goes on forever.** Set a hard cap. Ship the game. Iterate
in a post-release patch. Perfection is the enemy of shipping.

---

## 6.10 Try this yourself

1. Take chapter 2's paddle game. Add rotation-ease-style acceleration
   to paddle movement. Does the game feel better?
2. Add `world/camera-shake!` to the brick game — small shake on brick
   hit, big shake on paddle catch. Where does it feel right?
3. Wire buttons to display 'input echo' — the last 30 frames of button
   state as a scrolling bar. Now you can SEE your own inputs and
   debug feel.
4. Record your play with `world/tape-record!`. Replay it with feel-off
   and feel-on. Note which feels 'more like a game.'
5. Tune the tuning workbench: change knob-adjust rate so precision
   knobs (rot-acc, thr) adjust by 0.001 and coarse knobs (dead-x)
   adjust by 1.
6. Add sound: `(audio/play 'thrust)` while 'a' is held. Volume scales
   with `thrust-charge`.

---

## 6.11 What we built

Ease, deadzone, camera lag, impact-scaled shake, tuning workbench.
The eight knobs. `tick/ease` as the workhorse of every feel decision.
`motion/with-feel` and `motion/with-pace` as the polish-layer verbs.

Next chapter: the hardest simple thing in game design. The jump. Slow
apex hang, fast fall, generous coyote, generous buffer. Chapter 7 is
where a kid learns that feel is code by tuning ONE specific action
across ten specific frames.")

